<mujoco model="base">
  <compiler coordinate='local' angle='degree' eulerseq='xyz' boundmass='1e-5' boundinertia='1e-11'/>

  <!-- noslip_iterations MUST stay 0. mujoco_warp does not implement the noslip
       solver, and all training happens in Warp. This file used to say 5, so every
       dm_control eval graded Warp-trained policies under friction they had never
       seen. The worm propels itself entirely by pushing against the ground, which
       makes this the worst possible flag to have mismatched.

       Measured on follow_v2/final.pt over 12 fixed episodes, changing ONLY this
       value moved individual episodes by up to 330 points out of 600 (one
       "catastrophic failure" scoring 37.8 was actually 367.7 in the physics the
       policy trains in) and the mean by 44. It was inflating our failure rate and
       hiding real progress.

       The cost is accepted knowingly. Without the noslip pass, MuJoCo's soft
       constraint formulation lets contacts creep slightly under friction. We are
       not targeting real world transfer, so slightly soft contacts are fine.
       Being lied to by our own eval is not.

       (No doubled dashes in this comment: XML forbids them, and lxml, which
       dm_control's mjcf parser uses, rejects the whole file for it.) -->
  <option cone='elliptic' noslip_iterations='0' noslip_tolerance='0' timestep='0.0025'/>

  <visual>
    <global offwidth='1920' offheight='1080'/>
    <map znear='0.01'/>
    <headlight diffuse='.6 .6 .6'  ambient='.3 .3 .3' specular='0 0 0'/>
    <scale forcewidth='0.01' contactwidth='0.06' contactheight='0.01' jointwidth='.01' framewidth='.01' framelength='.3'/>
  </visual>
</mujoco>
